00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:58.060
Well, there's a way to sort of
help remember what the filling

00:04:58.060 --> 00:04:59.260
sequence is.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:06.560
And that rule is encapsulated by
the n plus l relationship.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:14.870
So for equivalent, n plus l
values, for equivalent n plus

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:21.900
l values, you fill
in ascending n.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:26.730
Fill in ascending n.

00:05:26.730 --> 00:05:28.580
So let's take a look.

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:31.630
So, here's Aufbau.

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:32.760
n plus l rule.

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:35.240
Here's an example where
we have 3d.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:38.020
d means l equals 2.

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:40.860
p means l equals 1. s
means l equals 0.

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:42.470
So 5 plus 0 is 5.

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:43.610
4 plus 1 is 5.

00:05:43.610 --> 00:05:45.090
3 plus 2 is 5.

00:05:45.090 --> 00:05:46.010
So what do I do?

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:52.200
Well, it's saying go in order
of ascending n plus l.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:56.740
And so, you can snake your way
through this n plus l, and get

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:59.500
the filling sequence for the
whole Periodic Table.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:00.500
So let's take a look.

00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:01.690
We'll start with 1s.

00:06:01.690 --> 00:06:02.980
Well, that's easy.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:04.610
That's hydrogen and helium.

00:06:04.610 --> 00:06:07.650
Then we go next to 2s.

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:09.330
There's lithium and beryllium.

00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:10.870
And then next goes 2p.

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:14.860
I mean, nobody's going to try
to stick 3s ahead of 2p.

00:06:14.860 --> 00:06:16.700
That's pretty straightforward.

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:19.020
2p, and that gets us all
the way over to neon.

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:21.350
And then we wrap around
over here to 3s.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:24.370
That gets us from sodium
to magnesium.

00:06:24.370 --> 00:06:28.950
And then we jump to
3p, gets us from

00:06:28.950 --> 00:06:30.680
aluminum over to argon.

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:35.850
And then, we don't go to 3d,
because 3p is 3 plus 1 is 4.

00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:38.160
4s is 4 plus 0 is 4.

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:41.950
So it says we fill
in ascending n.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:43.550
So we go to 4s next.

00:06:43.550 --> 00:06:45.990
And that gets us potassium
and calcium.

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:47.550
Then comes 3d.

00:06:47.550 --> 00:06:51.640
So that gets us scandium over
to zinc. Then comes 4p,

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:53.360
gallium to krypton.

00:06:53.360 --> 00:06:54.520
5s.

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:56.530
I'm having fun here, I'm
going to keep going.

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:59.230
5s gets us over to strontium.

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:01.270
Next comes 4d.

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:03.430
Gets us all the way
over to cadmium.

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:06.070
5p gets us to xenon.

00:07:06.070 --> 00:07:10.410
Now it's turn 6s
cesium, barium.

00:07:10.410 --> 00:07:11.295
4f.

00:07:11.295 --> 00:07:12.780
We've got to jump down here.

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:15.130
Finally we're going to
get to the f shell.

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:16.280
See?

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:17.670
The 4f is in here.

00:07:17.670 --> 00:07:22.430
Now, this is an item
of convenience.

00:07:22.430 --> 00:07:27.590
Strictly speaking, lanthanum
is 57, cerium is 58.

00:07:27.590 --> 00:07:30.730
So all of these elements
belong in here.

00:07:30.730 --> 00:07:33.400
But if we were to put this to
scale, the Periodic Table

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:34.245
would be way over here.

00:07:34.245 --> 00:07:35.940
It wouldn't fit on a page.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:38.810
So people, over time, have
gotten used to just

00:07:38.810 --> 00:07:39.750
putting it down here.

00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:42.680
But these elements are
in the middle here.

00:07:42.680 --> 00:07:48.670
So you go 4d, 5p, 6s, then 4f.

00:07:48.670 --> 00:07:51.180
Finally we get over to the edge
here, to erbium, and then

00:07:51.180 --> 00:07:55.110
we jump over here to hafnium,
5d, over to

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:59.410
mercury, 6p, et cetera.

00:07:59.410 --> 00:08:02.880
So the n plus l rule gives you
the filling sequence in

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:04.440
ascending order.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:05.500
That's good.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:08.910
So we've got a nice compact
way of grabbing this e

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:10.730
goes to n plus l.

